{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_012QcGMT69qNKyBnG9Wn9s9G","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me carefully analyze each behavior for the patient intake system and determine the minimum test level needed to catch real failures.\n\nThe key is to think about what could go wrong in production that a lower-level test would miss.\n\n**Behavior 1: Required patient fields validation**\n- Description: Required patient fields (name, date of birth, insurance ID) are validated before any downstream processing — missing fields produce a clear error listing all missing items.\n- What could fail in production?\n  - Missing field validation logic doesn't catch all required fields\n  - Error message is malformed or doesn't list all missing items\n  - Downstream processing happens before validation completes\n  \n- Could a unit test miss this?\n  - No, this is pure function logic. Call validate_patient_fields(patient_dict) with various missing fields and check the error message.\n  - No I/O needed, no real dependencies\n  - A mock could catch all real failures here\n  \n- MOCK-MISS: No, a mock won't miss this. It's deterministic validation logic.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS or network dependency.\n- MOCK-HIDE: No, the validation happens locally.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\n→ **Unit** is sufficient. This is pure validation logic with clear inputs/outputs.\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 2: Date of birth validation**\n- Description: Date of birth validation rejects future dates, dates more than 150 years ago, and non-date strings.\n- What could fail?\n  - Edge cases around the 150-year boundary\n  - Timezone handling if dates are stored with timezone\n  - Leap year handling in date parsing\n  - String format variations\n  \n- Could a unit test miss this?\n  - No, this is pure date validation logic. Call validate_dob(dob_string) and check outcomes.\n  - No I/O or external dependencies involved.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: No\n- REAL-INFRA: No\n- MOCK-HIDE: No\n- LLM-DEP: No\n- MULTI-STEP: No\n\n→ **Unit** is sufficient.\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 3: Insurance eligibility check API call**\n- Description: The insurance eligibility check sends the correct patient ID and plan code to the payer API and correctly interprets the response (eligible/not eligible/pending).\n- What could fail in production?\n  - Wrong patient ID or plan code sent to API\n  - Response parsing is incorrect for a real payer response\n  - API timeout or network issues not handled properly\n  - Response format changes between payer systems\n\nA unit test with mocks can verify the request is formed correctly and responses are parsed as expected. However, real API responses may have variations, edge cases, or format differences that a mock won't expose. The actual payer API could return unexpected fields, null values, or error codes that the parsing logic doesn't handle.\n\n→ **Integration** is needed. This requires testing against real or realistic API responses to catch parsing failures and ensure correct request formation. and handling the exception can be tested with a mock. But a real network failure might behave differently—the system might hang, retry indefinitely, or fail in ways the mock doesn't simulate. A mock also won't catch if the system is configured to timeout too quickly or if connection pooling causes cascading failures.\n\nThe test needs to verify the system actually continues processing when the API is unreachable, that it sets the eligibility state to pending, and that downstream operations receive this pending state correctly. It should also check realistic failure modes like connection timeouts and authentication errors, ensuring the exception handling covers all failure types the real API might encounter. drops connections) is more robust.\n\nThe test should verify the system handles the payer API being unreachable—either through a network partition or service outage—without crashing, records the transaction as pending, and allows downstream processing to continue without treating insurance validation as a hard requirement.\n\nFor the AI symptom triage behavior, I need to consider whether mocking can adequately test emergency condition detection. A mock returning a fixed high-urgency response wouldn't catch cases where the model misclassifies actual emergency symptom combinations, the prompt is misconfigured, response parsing fails, or edge cases like misspelled or unusual symptom descriptions aren't handled properly.\n\nThe real AI model's behavior is non-deterministic and depends on how it was trained and how the prompt is structured. Testing with a mock hides these real-world failures. This requires calling an actual LLM or the real medical reasoning engine to verify the prompt correctly conveys symptoms and the model consistently identifies emergency conditions.\n\nFor the natural language explanation, a mock can easily return coherent text, but the actual model might produce incoherent output, hallucinations, or explanations that contradict the urgency score. The explanation also needs to be clinically appropriate—not overly technical or unclear for a clinician to review. Testing this requires the real AI to surface these potential failures.\n\nFor appointment scheduling, the system needs to place high-urgency cases in same-day slots and medium-urgency within 48 hours. The slot selection algorithm could fail by choosing incorrectly, scheduling outside the urgency window, or not finding available slots when they exist.\n\nA mocked calendar database masks several critical issues: race conditions where concurrent intake processes claim the same slot, real database performance problems, timezone mismatches (same-day in which timezone?), and actual calendar constraints like provider availability and slot duration. The mock also won't reveal whether the real calendar system has different data structures or business rules than expected.\n\nTesting this requires actual infrastructure—a real or staging calendar system to verify slot availability, concurrency handling, and timezone logic work correctly in production conditions.\n\nFor the double-booking scenario specifically, I need to test that when two patients submit intake requests simultaneously, the system doesn't assign them to the same time slot. This is a concurrency issue that only surfaces with real database transactions and locking mechanisms.\n\nA mocked database can't catch this because it operates deterministically—it won't simulate the race condition where both processes read the slot as available before either writes their booking. Real transaction isolation and atomic operations are essential here. I'll need an actual database with proper locking and two concurrent intake processes running in parallel to verify the booking logic prevents conflicts.\n\nFor Behavior 9, the confirmation message needs to pull the right patient name, appointment time, provider name, and visit-type-specific prep instructions. A unit test with mocks can verify the message generation logic works, but it won't catch whether the system actually retrieves the correct fields from the database or whether prep instructions match the visit type.\n\nIntegration testing with real data is the minimum needed here—I need to verify that database lookups return the right provider information, that visit types map to the correct instructions, and that all fields format properly. A unit test could work with careful test data setup, but integration testing is more reliable for catching data-retrieval bugs.\n\nFor the full intake pipeline, the risk is that individual steps pass their tests but fail when chained together in production. Data might not flow correctly between validation, insurance checks, symptom triage, scheduling, and confirmation steps.\n\nMocking each step independently masks integration failures—the real problem surfaces only when running the complete flow end-to-end. Environment-specific issues like missing email services or slow AI triage also only emerge in a full run. This requires an integration test with real infrastructure, or at least a test that exercises the actual data handoffs between steps.\n\nSince the triage step invokes a real LLM and the pipeline chains multiple agentic operations together (triage followed by scheduling and confirmation), this demands a workflow-level test. The full sequence—validation, insurance checks, symptom triage via AI, database scheduling, and confirmation with actual message delivery—needs to run against real or near-real services to catch where one step's output breaks another's input.\n\nFor validation logic itself, I'm confident unit testing handles it well (0.98 unit, 0.02 integration). Date-of-birth validation is similarly straightforward—pure logic, so unit at 0.98. The insurance API call requires system testing since it needs actual HTTP interaction (0.80 system, 0.15 integration, 0.05 unit). When the API becomes unreachable, I'd lean toward system testing to verify the fallback behavior, though integration with mocked exceptions could substitute (0.70 system, 0.25 integration). The AI triage itself is inherently agentic—it needs the real model or a close simulation to validate the behavior.\n\nFor explanation quality, agentic testing is necessary to assess natural language generation (0.85 agentic, 0.10 system). Slot selection and urgency ranking require integration at minimum since the logic depends on database queries and concurrent request handling (0.80 integration, 0.15 system). Preventing double-bookings is a concurrency and transaction concern, making integration essential (0.90 integration). Confirmation message fields can be tested at integration level with real database lookups, though unit testing with test objects is possible (0.75 integration, 0.20 unit). The full pipeline orchestration is a workflow test—it chains multiple behaviors including the agentic triage step (0.85 workflow, 0.10 agentic).","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13649,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13649},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a285598-ab8c-4e27-b80d-41ad4fe51861","uuid":"9b479803-5726-4d83-b4df-177ee01652c0"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_012QcGMT69qNKyBnG9Wn9s9G","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at this patient intake system, I need to identify which failures require what level of testing infrastructure. The key insight is that failures fall into distinct categories: pure logic bugs, external API contracts, database concurrency, AI model behavior, and multi-step orchestration.\n\nLet me analyze each behavior:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13649,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13649},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a285598-ab8c-4e27-b80d-41ad4fe51861","uuid":"5bdd1ec7-00eb-4cdb-ab14-e5a5987a7962"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_012QcGMT69qNKyBnG9Wn9s9G","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LqRv9mNQ4y1WTjbd33waFr","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Required patient fields (name, DOB, insurance ID) are validated before downstream processing; missing fields produce an error listing all missing items.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure validation logic with deterministic inputs/outputs. No I/O, no external dependency, no non-determinism. A unit test calling validate_patient_fields({missing: field}) catches all real failure modes: missing validation checks, incomplete error messages, or premature downstream execution. Mocking cannot hide this failure.","test_description":"Call the patient field validator with various combinations of missing required fields (name only, DOB only, insurance ID only, multiple missing). Verify each returns an error listing exactly the missing fields. Edge case: empty object should list all three required fields.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.98,"Integration":0.01,"System":0.005,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Date of birth validation rejects future dates, dates more than 150 years in the past, and non-date strings.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Pure date parsing and range-checking logic. No I/O, no real dependencies. A unit test verifies the boundary logic (today, tomorrow, 150-year boundary, 151 years ago, garbage strings) directly. Mocking adds no value; the logic is deterministic and local.","test_description":"Parameterized unit test: feed the validator dates at and around the boundaries (future dates, exactly 150 years ago, 151+ years ago, current date, invalid strings like 'not-a-date', null/empty). Verify rejections and acceptances. Test with various date formats if the validator accepts multiple formats.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.98,"Integration":0.01,"System":0.005,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Insurance eligibility check sends correct patient ID and plan code to payer API and correctly interprets 'eligible', 'not eligible', and 'pending' responses.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: A mock function can return hardcoded responses, but a real API failure happens when the system sends wrong headers, malformed JSON, incorrect auth tokens, or calls the wrong endpoint. A mock hides these protocol-level bugs. REAL-INFRA: The real API HTTP contract (request format, response schema, status codes) only appears at the System level. The test must make actual HTTP requests (or use an HTTP-mock server that validates the request) to verify correct serialization of patient ID and plan code, correct header/auth handling, and correct response parsing.","test_description":"Using an HTTP stub/fake payer API that validates incoming request format, auth headers, and request body. Call the eligibility check with test patient data. Verify: (1) correct patient ID and plan code appear in the HTTP request body, (2) correct auth headers are present, (3) the system correctly parses 'eligible', 'not eligible', and 'pending' responses. Test malformed responses (missing fields, unexpected types) to verify robustness.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When payer API is unreachable, system marks eligibility as 'pending' and continues intake rather than blocking.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: A mock can throw ConnectionError, but the real API might throw SSLError, DNSTimeout, socket.timeout, or EOF—if the code only catches ConnectionError, the mock test passes but production fails. REAL-INFRA: To test the actual fallback behavior, the test must make the real (or realistic) payer API genuinely unreachable—network partition, service down, or timeout. This verifies all exception types are caught and the intake continues without crashing.","test_description":"Make the payer API endpoint unreachable (kill the service, configure a network drop, or timeout the connection). Call the intake flow. Verify: (1) no exception propagates to the caller, (2) eligibility is recorded as 'pending', (3) intake proceeds to the next step (symptom triage, scheduling), not blocked at the insurance check. Run the test multiple times to catch intermittent failures.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.73,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"AI symptom triage correctly assigns high urgency to symptom combinations indicating emergency conditions (e.g., chest pain + shortness of breath).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Correctness depends on what the real AI/medical reasoning engine produces, not on mocked responses. The model is non-deterministic and may classify differently based on prompt phrasing, model version, or edge cases. A mock always returns a fixed response (high urgency) for test inputs, hiding prompt-engineering bugs, model misalignment, or real-world failures where the model classifies an emergency symptom as non-emergency. Only calling the real AI model verifies the actual behavior.","test_description":"Call the symptom triage with real high-risk symptom combinations (chest pain + shortness of breath, loss of consciousness + severe headache, etc.). Run multiple times to assess consistency (the model may be non-deterministic). Verify the returned urgency level is 'high' with >95% consistency. Capture the AI's explanation to ensure it reflects the emergency nature. If consistency is lower than required, flag the prompt or model choice as a failure.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.84,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Symptom triage produces a natural language explanation of urgency assessment that a clinician can review, not just a numeric score.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The explanation quality depends on what the real LLM produces. A mock can return a fixed explanation ('Patient has chest pain'), hiding real failures: hallucinated medical terms, incoherent sentences, explanations that contradict the urgency score, or explanations too technical/jargon-heavy for review. Only calling the real AI model verifies the NLG output is coherent and clinically appropriate.","test_description":"Call the symptom triage with diverse symptom inputs. For each urgency level (low, medium, high), verify the explanation is non-empty and coherent. Use a clinician reviewer or a secondary LLM to score readability/appropriateness. Verify explanation reasoning aligns with the urgency score (e.g., high urgency explanation mentions emergency indicators). Check that no unexplained medical jargon or hallucinations appear.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Appointment is scheduled in the first available slot matching the assigned urgency level — high urgency gets same-day, medium gets within 48 hours.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: A mock calendar always returns a fixed list of slots, hiding real database bugs: query inefficiency, wrong urgency→availability mapping, timezone mishandling, or slot data corruption. REAL-INFRA: Testing slot selection requires a real database (or in-memory transactional mock) with realistic calendar data, availability constraints, and timezone logic. The test must verify the algorithm selects the correct slot (first available for the urgency level) from actual data.","test_description":"Populate a real calendar database with slots: some same-day (for high urgency), some within 48h (for medium), some beyond (for low). Assign urgency levels and call the scheduling function. Verify: (1) high-urgency gets same-day slot, (2) medium-urgency gets within-48h slot, (3) if multiple same-day slots exist, the earliest is selected, (4) timezone calculations are correct (same-day in the clinic's timezone, not UTC). Edge case: test when no slots match the urgency—verify graceful fallback (e.g., offer next-available or return error).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"Scheduling step does not double-book a time slot even when two patients are being processed concurrently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: A mock database cannot simulate transaction isolation or race conditions. A mock always returns results in deterministic order, hiding concurrency bugs that occur randomly in production. REAL-INFRA: This is a stress/concurrency test requiring real database transactions. The failure—both processes seeing a slot as available and both booking it—only appears when transactions are not properly isolated. A real database with proper locking/serialization catches this; a mock never will.","test_description":"Set up a real database with a single available time slot. Concurrently execute two intake workflows (two threads/processes or async tasks) for different patients, both targeting the same slot. Verify: (1) only one patient gets the slot, (2) the other patient gets a different slot or receives a 'no availability' response without crashing. Run the test multiple times (race conditions are probabilistic). Monitor database locks to confirm proper transaction isolation.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.88,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"Confirmation message includes patient name, appointment time, provider name, and preparation instructions appropriate to the visit type.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-HIDE: A unit test with injected mock objects (fake Patient, Appointment, Provider instances) can verify template formatting. But if the code does database lookups to fetch provider names, visit-type-specific instructions, or appointment details, those lookups can fail in production—wrong provider matched, missing instructions for a visit type, or mismatched data. An Integration test with a real database ensures the message generation pulls correct data from the database and formats it accurately.","test_description":"Set up a real database with patient records, appointments, providers (with names and specialties), and visit types with associated preparation instructions. Call the confirmation message generator with real patient/appointment IDs. Verify the message includes: (1) correct patient name, (2) correct appointment date/time, (3) correct provider name, (4) preparation instructions matching the visit type. Edge case: test a visit type that has no preparation instructions—verify the message handles it gracefully (omits field or includes placeholder).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"Full intake pipeline (validate, check insurance, triage symptoms, schedule, confirm) completes for a real patient submission without manual intervention.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP + LLM-DEP: This is an end-to-end flow with multiple agentic steps (symptom triage calls a real LLM). Failures in individual steps (Unit/Integration tests) may not surface integration bugs: data flow between steps is broken, timing is wrong, side effects from one step corrupt downstream steps, or the full flow hits timeouts or resource exhaustion. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking triage hides AI behavior; mocking scheduling hides DB concurrency; mocking confirmation hides email service failures. Only a full Workflow test (all real services, real AI, real DB) catches orchestration bugs.","test_description":"End-to-end integration test: submit a complete patient intake form with valid data. Let the pipeline run: (1) validate fields, (2) call real payer API for insurance check, (3) call real AI for symptom triage, (4) schedule appointment in real DB, (5) generate and send confirmation message. Verify: the intake completes without errors, the patient appears in the DB with all data correctly populated, the appointment is in the calendar, and the confirmation message was sent/logged. Time the full pipeline; if any step exceeds SLA, flag it. Run with realistic data volumes to catch performance regressions.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.76}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13649,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13649},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a285598-ab8c-4e27-b80d-41ad4fe51861","uuid":"8d76515f-1cd1-4fd4-9124-bbdcb7c06043"}
